# 4. What actually works

## A. Hidden-problem reframes

This is one of the strongest patterns in the entire feed.

John often takes a visible complaint and replaces it with the real underlying issue.

Examples of the pattern:
- your dependency problem is largely a prioritization problem
- simplification conversations are often cost-cutting conversations in disguise
- process often exists to avoid discipline, not create it
- outcomes discourse becomes nonsense when it ignores causality in complex systems
- digital transformation advice breaks when copied into the wrong context

Why this works:
- it respects the reader's intelligence
- it gives them better language
- it cuts through superficial diagnosis
- it feels like hard-won pattern recognition

## B. False-precision critique

Another major winner.

John performs very well when attacking:
- fake certainty
- over-commitment rituals
- precision theater in roadmaps, estimates, and plans
- stack-ranking nonsense
- fantasy planning detached from history

Why it works:
- almost every operator has lived this
- it is concrete, not abstract
- it lets readers feel seen
- it gives leaders a saner alternative

## C. AI panic, AI posturing, and executive anxiety

This theme performs extremely well.

Not "AI is changing everything."
That is too generic.

What works instead:
- AI as theater
- AI as pressure transfer from leaders to employees
- AI as investor signaling
- AI as a new excuse for layoffs, urgency, and ideology
- AI as something useful only when grounded in real work

Why it works:
- it captures the present moment
- it gives readers emotional language for what they are seeing
- it cuts through both blind hype and lazy cynicism

## D. Leadership and management culture critique

Strong recurring pattern.

Examples:
- middle management being scapegoated
- leadership copying the wrong playbook
- management culture rewarding the wrong things
- leaders confusing control with clarity
- strategic decisions being less disciplined than technical decisions

Why it works:
- it names power structures directly
- it helps readers stop personalizing systemic problems
- it feels brave without being empty

## E. Satire and parody posts

This is not fluff content.
It is one of the sharpest weapons in the feed.

Strong examples:
- fake AI memos
- "vibe leadership"
- absurd all-in startup parody
- fake corporate 2025 vibes guides
- parody book formulas for leaders

Why it works:
- fast recognition
- highly shareable
- emotionally sticky
- punches up at management theater
- creates belonging among people who "get it"

## F. Lightweight operational principles

John also wins with posts that sound like simple advice, but are rooted in deep systems thinking.

Examples:
- only define the small number of things that truly need to be global
- release notes are an easy honesty mechanism
- start with rituals and interactions before over-codifying
- progressively disclose roadmap detail
- autonomy requires a few clear interfaces, not endless standardization

Why it works:
- practical
- portable
- not overbuilt
- easy to share with teams

## G. Book and discourse critique

This is a smaller but important pattern.

He sometimes reacts to:
- famous product books
- big-name thinkers
- public debates on social media
- widely accepted organizational ideas

These posts work best when he is not just reacting.
They work when he uses the reaction to expose a bigger pattern.

